<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Soviet Union has increased its military presence in the Persian Gulf since 
the Iran-Iraq cease-fire despite publicly urging withdrawal of foreign navies 
from the region, a top U.S. commander said in Manama, Bahrain. "I see no 
withdrawal of the Soviets in this area," said Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf, who 
commands U.S. forces in the gulf in his post as chief of the U.S. Central 
Command. "As a matter of fact . . . I see an increase in their diplomatic 
initiatives . . . and their military assistance initiatives." Schwarzkopf said 
there has been a gradual reduction of U.S. forces in the gulf since the Aug. 20 
cease-fire but that the United States will keep at least six warships in the 
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
