<P>
JOINT SEARCH FOR MIAS IN LAOS TO GO AHEAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The government of Laos has agreed to go forward with a joint search for missing 
American servicemen that was delayed two weeks ago because of a dispute over a 
U.S. report that listed Laos and Burma as major drug sources, the State 
Department said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Charles Redman said the U.S.-Laotian mission, which had been set for 
March 4, will take place shortly, with a team of American experts due to arrive 
in Laos on Saturday. It will be the fifth joint U.S.-Laotian mission to search 
for 547 American servicemen still listed as missing in Laos from the Vietnam 
War. 
