<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: POP LP CHART; 
</P>
<P>
ABDUL'S 'GIRL' SHOOTS UP CHART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DENNIS HUNT , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Paula Abdul may turn out to be the most popular female dance-music artist since 
Janet Jackson was controlling the pop charts a few years ago. Abdul's "Forever 
Your Girl" album -- up to No. 4 on the Billboard magazine pop chart -- just 
crossed the 1-million mark. Fine Young Cannibals' album -- "The Raw and the 
Cooked" (No. 16) -- is by far the hottest new release of the last few weeks. 
Madonna's "Like a Prayer" single, No. 25 in just two weeks, looks like a Top 10 
shoo-in. 
</P>
<P>
* Guitarist Vernon Reid is having the last laugh on all those skeptics who said 
his Living Colour, like just about every other black rock band, would never 
make it. But he insisted their "Vivid" album was too good to ignore. Fans 
eventually agreed. The album, slow to catch on, finally made the Top 10 -- at 
No. 9. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
