<P>
ITC Ruling: The U.S. International Trade Commission ruled 4-1 that Japanese 
firms were dumping microdisks on the U.S. market, paving the way for the 
Commerce Department to levy anti-dumping duties. The commission, which monitors 
compliance to U.S. trade law, ruled the imports sold at less than fair market 
value were injuring American firms making the disks that are widely used in 
portable computers. It acted on a complaint filed on behalf of the U.S. 
industry by Verbatim Corp. of Charlotte, N.C. Domestic manufacturers have long 
complained that the Japanese have violated U.S. trade rules. The disks are big 
sellers for use in the increasingly popular laptop or travel computers. 
