<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
EKLUND SCORES WORLD BOXING TITLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
RENO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Anders Eklund of Sweden overcame a sixth-round knockdown to earn a decision 
Thursday night over Philip Brown of New Orleans and claim the vacant World 
Boxing Assn. Americanus heavyweight championship. 
</P>
<P>
Brown, a former sparring partner for former heavyweight champion Larry Holmes, 
stunned Eklund with a looping right hand midway through the sixth round. He 
followed up with two more roundhouse rights, sending Eklund to the canvas. 
</P>
<P>
Brown, however, did little else throughout the 12-round bout, throwing only 
four combinations before the sellout crowd of 1,000 at Harrah's Reno. 
</P>
<P>
Eklund, a 6-foot-6-inch, 253-pound European champion, jabbed weakly but was 
effective in throwing solid body shots. 
</P>
<P>
Eklund won handily on two cards. The third judge, Doug Tucker, scored the fight 
a 114-114 draw. Eklund improved to 18-4-1, while Brown dropped to 36-4. 
</P>
<P>
Eklund has signed to fight Italy's Guido Turne for the European heavyweight 
championship. The bout is scheduled May 10 in Helsinki. 
</P>
</TEXT>
